Women who are labeled witches in Burkina Faso usually have some common social characteristics.
They are more likely to belong to the older generation, they do not find work - for example, for health reasons, they are single and do not have children.
When one of these women "becomes" a witch, she is strictly isolated so that she cannot become dangerous to the rest of the village.
“Men are rarely affected by this fate.”
“Even young and healthy women are spared this because they help to work and give birth to children,” a nun describes the situation in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso, where more than one hundred women were cared for by their communities in a special home.
The local government has now decided to take action against this abnormal "social measure".
And for this reason, he issued a brochure to prevent "witch persecution".
But the thing has a hook.
"More than 70 percent of all adults in Burkina Faso cannot read," the newspaper "derStandard" pointed out to the dilemma of written enlightenment.
But to be accused of witchcraft is also commonplace in other African countries.
In Ghana, the neighboring country of Burkina Faso, the 27-year-old Ammy Hemmahová was tortured to death by three women and two men – they poured petroleum over her and simply set her on fire.
The incident was reported by the BBC server.
The perpetrators, however, claimed that the matter was only a coincidence of unfortunate circumstances.
According to their version, oil is inflamed, which is used for ritual anointing.
After the group tried to "eject an evil spirit" from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" supports the people here regardless of their education.
“The Standard” quoted a 42-year-old entrepreneur from Burkina Faso: “Freshers of human souls are a danger before as they are today,” he said.
While the government in Burkina Faso is at least trying to defuse the witch hunt, the Gambian president himself has mixed up last year.
“President Yahya Jammeh ignited a monstrous witch hunt after his aunt’s death, as they allegedly had a share in their deaths and would now try to kill the president himself by black magic.”
“To this end, he called on shamans from nearby Guinea who, accompanied by police officers, soldiers and the President’s bodyguard, forcibly abducted women and men from Gambian villages and brought them to the President’s farm in Kanilai,” Amnesty International said in its report.
On the farm, the imprisoned people were forced to drink an absud of plants with a hallucinogenic effect, which also caused intestinal and kidney problems.
