A longer index finger than a ring finger means a lower risk of developing cancer
Men whose index fingers are longer than the ring finger are obviously at a lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising result of a study published Wednesday by the British Journal of Cancer.
This is related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that relative finger length can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer, particularly in men up to sixty," said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Cancer Research Institute at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should definitely undergo a prostate cancer test, especially if genetic risks or other risk factors are present, such as family health burdens, Ms Eeles added.
In the period 1994-2009, she and her colleagues in Britain followed more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer, but also 3,000 healthy men at the same time.
In more than half of the study participants, the index finger of the right hand was shorter than the ring finger.
For these men, the same probability of prostate cancer was applied as for 19 percent of those men whose ring and index fingers were the same length.
In men whose index fingers were longer than the ring finger, however, this risk decreased by 33 percent, in men up to 60 even by 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers mentioned, which form as early as prenatal age, obviously reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the child was exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index finger.
Previous research has shown that testosterone in particular accelerates the growth of prostate cancer.
Václav Pa<0xC4><0x8D>es, a leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, said <0xC4><0x8C>TK was fleetingly aware of the study but did not consider the relationship between finger length and cancer risk to be "completely proven".
