The democracy movement in Latin America is becoming stronger, as is the support of private companies.
Crime is a bigger problem than unemployment.
In many parts of the region, Brazil’s influence is greater than that of the United States.
The Latinobarometer survey was conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist.
This survey has been carried out regularly since 1995 and thus shows the change of opinion in this region.
Two facts are particularly relevant in this year’s September and October survey.
First, the good mood in Latin America
and the growing interest in democracy and its most important institutions.
In many countries on the South American Pacific coast, the democratic movement has increased sharply (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has grown by about 6% annually since 2002, the number of proponents of democracy rose from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
This trend is also evident in Mexico, where the economy has recovered since last year’s sharp downturn.
But only half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the most populous countries in the region, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see Chart 2).
Approximately 44% of respondents stated that they were satisfied with their country’s democratic practice. That is as many as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (Diagram 3).
Approximately 34% trust the Congress of their country and 45% of their government, both of which are in line with last year’s figures, but show a significant increase compared to 2003 (17% and 24%).
A decade ago, Latin America’s economic crises undermined efforts for more democracy.
This continued during the global economic crisis, perhaps, because the countries of Latin America experienced only a short period of recession and quickly recovered.
In addition, the poor were caught by a stronger social network.
(According to reports by the UN Economic Commission for Latin America this week, the poverty rate in Latin America rose only slightly in 2009 and fell again by 32% this year.)
However, there are strong differences in moods between countries (see Chart 4).
Brazil’s strong economy and the popularity of outgoing President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva is reflected in a widespread thinking of progress.
In Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more noticeable and violent crimes have increased, this is less the case.
For the second time since the start of the survey, many respondents in Latin America see crime in their country as a bigger problem than unemployment (see Figure 5).
About 31% say that either they themselves or a family member were victims of a crime last year, but compared to 38% last year, the values have fallen, reaching the lowest level since 1995.
Increasing economic performance is reflected in stronger support for the private and market economies: 71% of respondents supra-regionally stated that the private sector is essential for development, in 2007 it was 56% (see Chart 6).
About 58% said that only the market economy can make progress in their country, compared with 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela have maintained this view (and 80% are for a private sector), although their left-wing president, Hugo Chávez, nationalizes many private companies.
According to 19% of respondents (18% last year), Brazil has the largest weight in the region, followed by the United States (9%, unchanged since last year) and Venezuela (9% compared to 11% last year).
Respondents in Mexico and most Central American countries, on the other hand, see the United States as the most influential country, with Venezuela taking over this role in the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
