Four girls, barely growing out of teenage age, wearing white gloves and identical olive green jackets and trousers stood tight.
Four pairs of black pumps stood in a straight row.
Four neat hats sat perfectly on the hair held with blue-and-white stripes.
"They look average to me," Mr. Tang remarked scornfully.
"Models are pretty."
Several governments have already tried to polish up the image of China’s city inspectors.
In a city, all new applicants must have a university degree.
The province of Guangdong introduced a bright blue uniform instead of the gray-green one.
Wuhan in Central China replaced violence with low staring: In 2009, 50 officials reportedly circled a improperly positioned snack car and stared at the operator until he packed up after half an hour and left the square.
Xindu, a district in Chengdu with 680,000 inhabitants, wants to fundamentally change the image.
Since 2003, 13 women have been reinforcing the urban police strips. They have been selected special because of their appearance, their good figure and their youth.
They should give the coarse police a softer, feminine aspect.
Unfortunately, Scarlett Johansson would not be able to improve the bad image that the Chinese have of these city commandos.
