Can politeness connect the dividing?
After a campaign of insults and negativity, little politeness has erupted in Washington this week.
Is it the omen of genuine two-party cooperation or a moment of illusion before one quickly returns to the struggle of the parties in the capital?
The meeting on Tuesday between President Obama and congressional leaders did not bring any breakthroughs in the major issues to be dealt with during the so-called “lame duck session,” the session at the end of a government period in which decisions are no longer taken.
From what you hear, it was neither a polite discussion between two different sides nor an observance of their shared responsibility to govern, but rather an empty episode of a partisan point-gathering.
The public meeting of the President’s Deficit Commission on Wednesday was also civilized, despite the political differences that continue between the members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months creates mutual respect that obscures the ideological divide that continues to separate members.
This is hardly enough to claim that a new era of cooperation has begun.
Both sides are now in a test phase - in which one of the other calls for a sign of cooperation and compromise, while one tries to weigh the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters after a renewed party warfare.
Therefore, the meeting on Tuesday itself and its assessment by the participants were limited to a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and too deep to expect a rapid change in the atmosphere that has prevailed over the past two years.
Whether it’s about taxes, donations, health or expectations, the two sides are miles apart.
Last but not least, the November election in Washington voted mildly for at least a short time.
“No question, the tone has changed,” said Pete Wehner, an official representative of the Bush administration who now works for the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
“This is inevitable after the election.
Elections arouse partisan passions that die again.
And that's good."
On some issues, especially those on the agenda of the “lame duck session,” Republicans and Democrats have little choice but to find a solution.”
Bush’s tax cuts end at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of that.
Both sides want to find a way to get some or even all of them, whether temporary or permanent.
Similarly, a compromise on increased unemployment pay is to be expected, albeit only because Republicans cannot afford to believe favored tax cuts for the rich while denying support to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, optimism has increased that these issues can be agreed during the "lame duck session" and at the same time ratify the New START Treaty.
But William Glaston of the Brookings Institution warns that a successful cooperation on pressing issues of the lame duck session "does not necessarily lead to a lasting cooperation of the parties when the new 112th Congress is convened in January.
Instead, he says, a phase of mismatch is more likely, perhaps even inevitable.
“After the things that need to be done are done, this short-term psychology will turn into confrontation,” he said.
Wehner is also skeptical - and this skepticism is shared by many - which leads to genuine cooperation.
“I see a lot of what’s going on from today to 2012 as a pre-match, or shadow boxes, for the main event of 2012,” he said.
The reasons for this have a lot to do with the presentation of the new Republican majority in the White House and with the tea party voters who served their education.
As concerned as the Republican leaders may be that they are playing poker too high, they know that they must try to keep their promises to cut government spending and overturn health care reform.
These party lines are already evident in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the Deficit Commission, which include tax reform and the raising of some taxes, as well as the raising of the retirement age and the lowering of government spending.
Vice Presidents Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, in their own view, have pushed so hard to put the deficit issue on the public agenda that it can no longer be ignored.
But they need within the Commission 14 of the 18 votes to make their plan the official recommendation and they are struggling hard to even get close to that number.
The greatest resistance is found in the elected representatives of the body, because in financial matters, at least today, there is little room or little sympathy for compromises.
Galston predicts two phases in the battle between the White House and Republicans in Congress.
The first fight will take place next year in the form of party clashes, as Republicans challenge Obama over the state budget, taxes and health care system, later followed by a phase of larger two-party cooperation.
What will lead to this change?
The public opinion.
It is proven that, despite the partiality of the current election, the majority of Americans still want the two parties to work together.
If confrontation leads to a dead end, as happened in 1995, then both parties must pay careful attention to the public response.
Whoever is condemned to lose will have to change course and seek compromise.
This may be an optimistic view.
Partiality and polarization are greater today than in the mid-1990s, and they seem to be a greater ideological divide between Obama and the Republicans than they were between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans.
At the same time, the activists of both parties see 2010 as a pure prelude to a far more far-reaching election in 2012.
From this point of view, the courtesy shown this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on both sides to find a common denominator in the questions that still separate the two.
Leaked US document portrays Moscow as port of corruption
The control of the city is in the hands of the "kleptocracy" and it passes some of the bribes and protection money it collects to the Kremlin, the American embassy in Russia reported in February in a memo.
Both the police and the state security service are extorting high protective funds so that they can maintain their expensive living standards in Moscow, it is said.
They raise money not only from legitimate businesses, but also from organized criminal gangs.
Every layer of bureaucracy – what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called the “vertical of authority” – takes its share of the money that moves the ladder up.
The memo, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was posted on its homepage Tuesday by WikiLeaks.
The memo is based on sources whose names have been edited.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still the mayor of Moscow, and it accuses him of corruption.
He was fired in October by President Dmitry Medvedev, but there is little evidence that he would have been cleaned up in the meantime.
Luzhkov and his wife, Yelena Baturina, who owns a well-known construction company, have repeatedly rejected allegations of corruption for years, and he has won numerous libel lawsuits against such allegations.
In September, he told a Russian TV station when asked about a documentary suggesting he was corrupt: "It's crazy, it's dirty, it's dirty."
> An incredibly large number of Russians believe that their society is corrupt, polls have found.
But it is unusual that, as happened in the Ambassador’s report, individual persons are mentioned, and it is unheard of for this to be done by a diplomat of a foreign country.
"The direct link between the Moscow government and crime has led some to call it 'disturbed' and conclude that the government is acting more like a kleptocrat than a government," the memo said.
"Criminal elements enjoy a 'kryshna' (a term from the world of criminals / the mafia, which literally means 'roof' or protection) that extends across the police, state security (FSB), the Service Supervisory Authority (MVD) and the Office of the Prosecutor as well as the entire Moscow government bureaucracy.
Experts have discovered a three-layered structure within the criminal world of Moscow.
"Luzhkov is at the top."
"FSB, MVD and the militia are on the second level."
“Lastly, the ordinary criminals and criminal inspectors follow at the lowest level.”
“This is an incompetent system in which criminal groups fill a gap in some areas because the city does not offer any help.”
The report goes on to say that the FSB collects money from the biggest companies and that the police arrest small businessmen.
One source, it is said, “explained that Moscow’s business owners understand that it is best to get protection from the MVD and FSB (and not from organized crime) as they not only have more weapons, resources and power than the criminals, but also because they are protected by law.”
“That’s why criminal gang protection isn’t as much in demand as it used to be.”
The memo notes that while collecting the funds is comprehensive, the protection itself will not be very modest; even those who pay are sometimes arrested.
Those who do not pay find their business closed very quickly - due to one or another pretext.
Medvedev has spoken on several occasions about tackling corruption, but at the same time noted that he has made little progress.
The memo of the embassy contains descriptions of men who went to the Kremlin with suitcases that were presumably full of money.
“In his fight against corruption, Medvedev must rely on the bureaucrats,” Georgy Satarov, director of Indem, a Moscow commission of experts, said in an interview recently.
“But he’s part of this bureaucracy.”
“It is not part of the political class because a political class no longer exists in Russia.”
Without politicians, without opposition, without a separation of powers, he says, corruption is inevitable.
Nationwide, Indem estimates, corruption costs Russia more than $300 billion a year.
The country ranks 154th in a recent survey of the global perception of corruption by the non-governmental organization Transparency International (countries listed from "least corrupt" to "most corrupt").
The unveiling of the memo of the American embassy, which took place late in the evening after Moscow time, will certainly provoke displeasure within the Russian government, although, since Luzhkov can be accused of Moscow’s mistakes, it can also be a way for the Kremlin to claim that the problems are solved.
In an interview with Larry King for CNN, Putin claimed that the WikiLeaks documents could be a forgery and reacted angryly to the revelation that American diplomats have called him Batman and Medvedev Robin.
“The truth is that it’s about our interaction, which is an important factor of domestic policy in this country,” he said.
“But to be honest, we didn’t expect this to happen with such arrogance, with such pressure, and in such an unethical way, you know.”
Khmer Rouge veterans forced to confront the past
In a dimly lit, concrete classroom with dirty and flaky walls, the director of Anlong Veng High School reminds the man who built it of the later Khmer Rouge leader Ta Mok.
"Everyone here loves Ta Mok."
“He was a good leader and he took care of his people,” said 42-year-old Sreng Kor Ma.
Because of his brutality during the Khmer Rouge rule known as "the butcher", the commander remains popular in this remote former Khmer Rouge stronghold in northwestern Cambodia, where he built hospitals and bridges, developed the infrastructure, and where thousands of former soldiers still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered to the government, longtime supporters are being challenged in Anlong Veng.
In April, a local Truth and Reconciliation Forum allowed victims to publicly confront the people who once supported the regime.
In June, the government distributed a schoolbook that tells the story of the Khmer Rouge for the first time to children of former soldiers.
And in July, a UN and Cambodian community tribunal first sentenced a former Khmer Rouge member to 35 years in prison when it sentenced the former head of the infamous Tuol Sleng torture chamber, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Duch.
With each of these developments, fear grew among the Khmer Rouge veterans of Alnlong Veng, making their efforts to reconcile and reintegrate into Cambodian society more difficult.
“There is still rejection and fear in the former Khmer Rouge, but they have no power to do anything,” said Chhang Youk, head of Cambodia’s Documentation Center, an independent organization that researches the regime.
"For her, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil."
“It divides even families.”
During the Khmer Rouge rule in Cambodia, between 1975 and 1979, an estimated 1.7 million people were executed or died of illness, overhaul or starvation.
When the Vietnamese invaded and the Pol Pot-Ied government overthrew in 1979, the remnants of the regime and its military fled to the Cambodian border with Thailand.
Here they spread unrest until December 1998, when the last movement capitulated.
When Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led the guerrilla war from their base in the western mountains and jungles of Cambodia, Ta Mok drew the next generation to Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, when a UN-sponsored peace agreement led to the country’s first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began to overrun the government, leading to the surrenders of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuan Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died a natural death in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had not given in, was arrested by government forces at the Dangrek Mountains in 1999.
He died in 2006 in Phnom Penh prison, where he was awaiting trial.
When their patrons no longer protected them, most of the former Khmer Rouge fighters fled to the crushing poverty of rural Cambodia, and many kept the movement in nostalgic memory.
Even though a few elitist Khmer Rouge officials kept their local government posts because they laid down their weapons, the simple soldiers remained poor, uneducated peasants.
"These people have benefited very little from the surrender," said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which holds public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
“They are anchored in the regime’s utopian agrarian ideology.”
“They grew up without any professional knowledge.”
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Rhmer Rouge in 1974 as a teenager, fought for Anlang Veng in the jungle before settling down in 1998 to lead a life as a poor rice farmer.
“Life under the Khmer Rouge was good,” he said.
"Ta Mok gave everyone something to eat."
“But now life is hard because we have to take care of ourselves.”
The current Khmer Rouge Tribunal has also raised concerns here.
Earlier next year, the court will try to prosecute Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, as well as Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister.
The task of the court is to condemn the old leaders and those who are primarily responsible for the atrocities, but it is not said whether it will prosecute further acts beyond these four cases.
This has done little to alleviate the fears in Anlong Veng.
Current media speculation has focused on Im Chaem, 64, who had been district chief in Manteay Meanchey province during the Khmer Rouge rule in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told Cambodia’s Documentation Centre commissioners that she had led the construction of the Trapeang Thma Dam, a project in which thousands of forced labourers were believed to have died.
One hot evening, Im Chaem returned from work in the fields to her wooden house on a dirty road outside Anlong Veng.
When the sun cast long shadows on the withered grass, Im Chaem refused to discuss her past at the Khmer Rouge.
If the court summoned her, she would refuse to leave, she said.
“Cambodia lives in peace and stability,” she said.
“If there were no more persecutions, there would be war here.”
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who fled the Khmer Rouge in 1878, has also repeatedly warned that the situation would become uncertain if the court would charge more suspects, although experts and historians discuss this.
"Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past," he said.
But confronting the past is what Cambodia needs to do to move forward, said Chhang Youk of the Documentation Center.
“Reconciling with the Khmer times means gathering the broken pieces,” he said.
"It is our duty to put these broken parts together so that they can understand everything."
