How are these processes to be understood?
It is anticipated that Merkel’s position is not a mistake in her public relations work.
On the contrary, it is a new round in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
Germany is adopting a fundamentally new perspective on shaping our future, which clashes with the maintenance of the ancient traditions of most of its partners.
In view of the resistance in Europe, Germany is beginning to speculate on three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first: a strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the South would have to leave the euro area.
The second: the reintroduction of the German Mark - although at the moment this sounds more like science fiction - supported by a large part of the public opinion, about 50 percent of the population.
The third: a restructuring of the euro according to German proposals, which means: more macroeconomic control; strict budgetary management; punishment of countries that fail to comply; possible withdrawal of payments from some countries, as well as the expansion of the costs of potential adjustment measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been showing for some time, so there are no excuses now.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission created incentives for deficits and the German government pulled out of its hands a constitutional reform to prevent this from 2016.
This was the first sign of the disconnect between what Germany considered necessary (strict tax plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second sign was set by the Central European country, when Merkel painfully postponed the decision to rescue Greece.
But the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, the public opinion and the published opinion were absolutely against a rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel comes out again with a clear position, calling for a reform of the European Union’s agreements to allow the rescue of a country while at the same time obliging private lenders to bear part of the costs.
This position was interpreted as anti-European, as it drove forward the Irish crisis and all that followed.
But their proposal, albeit somewhat sweetened, has been adopted, and in the coming months we will participate in the reform of the European Union, which is to enable these measures from 2013 onwards.
Germany has drawn a red line, which it does not intend to cross.
It tells everyone that - even if unpopular measures have to be taken now - the old way of functioning of the euro will no longer exist from this date.
2013 will be the year of the birth of a new currency area in which the infringing countries can be severely punished, forced to declare themselves insolvent, in which case the private sector will have to bear part of the costs.
Germany shows us that we have to embark on a hard growth course, with high savings and investment rates, moderate consumption, improved productivity and competitiveness, and positive external economic balances.
The other alternative, which is based on debt and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, as cited by Spain in boom times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we would do badly to not understand it.
It is not just about reducing the government deficit to 3% by 2013.
The demands are much tougher.
And the worst thing we could do under these conditions is to deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will be more calm.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunities offered to us by the spring of 2013.
It seems that Zapatero understood this as well, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after the meeting with the big companies last Saturday and the announcement of new measures from yesterday) indicates that despite the criticism of Merkel, the hypothesis of creating order in her own house has prepared its way.
But the red line drawn from Germany is there, and it doesn’t look like anything would change.
Among the possibilities considered is that we should not have to leave the euro area, which has been completely blocked with little reputable countries.
In this case, Germany could still tell us that it warned us.
Sports and rule circumvention
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against Ajax show an inventive spirit, but not the will to bypass a sanction.
