As is well known, the two players lost a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had already clearly won) time and played several fouls for the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid would lead his group, the two players will comply with the prescribed sanction in the next league game against Auxerre and thus enter the next phase without cards.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee punished the club's coach, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card in such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is more common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos – the unwritten but adhered to rules in this sport.
Part of the debate over the case depicted is that a Real Madrid football club team (who in his anthem claimed nobility and honor and on other occasions had punished its players for similar incidents) played the lead in this, and the dramatization by Mourinho, who added an episode more to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this behaviour, which is explicitly prohibited by the statutes, does not contradict the principles of sport, that is, whether these acts constitute a circumvention of the rules, which in fact is consistent with the statutes of the sport, but seems to circumvent its meaning.
In this matter, the damage caused to the sports spirit should be investigated.
The sports spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not endangered by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to prevent the opposing players from gaining an unjustified benefit from the opposing team.
The paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not correspond to what we usually understand by false play or rule circumvention, because the circumvention of the rule was not secretly carried out to avoid a sanction, but it should be as striking as possible so that it is punished by the referee.
The players waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders drew from the intentional fouls.
It should be emphasized here that the rival was neither placed in a less favourable position nor required advantages for the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club then does not have these players.
The advantage is obviously that players start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it is a long-term advantage, to a certain degree uncertain, as the team could eventually also retire. In addition, with this approach, players will receive a sanction and move on to the second card cycle, in which they leave with a card less than in the first cycle due to card accumulation.
It is not clear whether this is really an advantage.
Ultimately, such practices are not directed against the sporting spirit, which also includes strategic decisions to make the most of the regulations.
In this case, players did not want to bypass a penalty (this would actually be a clear case of rule bypass), they were more likely to choose when to undergo it.
They made a strategic decision without evading or escaping punishment.
Although the boundary between invention and rule environment is blurred, I believe this is a clear case of invention.
I have the impression that the controversy arose as a result of two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the nature of the provoked rule transfer.
The damage inflicted on the principles of sport by these actions is less ethical than aesthetic.
