The United States changes the rules for obtaining a visa
Persons must introduce themselves to the visa application service points at the consulate before their conversation; costs will be reduced by waiting times.
As of January 10, 2011, the procedures for applying for a visa at the U.S. embassy and consulates will change.
In the new procedure, most applicants must introduce themselves to the Visa Application Service Centres (ASCs) before they meet at the consulate.
ASC staff will record the applicant’s biometric data, which will be checked by the Consulate prior to the conversation.
The new procedure has certain advantages for the aspirants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa decreases because it is no longer necessary to pay separately for the appointment, the processing of the visa application and the transport service with which the document is handed over.
The applicant only makes a single payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the counter price is $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with an application (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for hands and investors.
Those who only want to extend their visa do not have to have a conversation at the consulate, they only have to imagine themselves at the nearest ASC, where they will present their documents and take their fingerprints.
Since the biometric data is collected in the ASC, applicants who need a second appointment for the conversation at the consulate remain there less time than before.
Those who apply for the visa at the consulates of Ciudad Juarez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer have to pay the service surcharge of $26.
Additional information on the new visa application procedure can be found on the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
