Global plan to renew lighting
In Cancun, the UN proposed a plan to renew lighting for households, trade and industry in 100 countries with a view to achieving a reduction in greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions, equivalent to nearly a third of the additional reduction needed to be realized to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its place in the footsteps of the concrete major projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun in order to compensate for the absence of mandatory reduction commitments from the developed countries.
According to the plan put forward yesterday, the main problem in the form of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of CFCs released to the earth due to illumination would be avoided if the white glow bulbs, which still represent a monopoly of 50 to 70% on the market, were replaced by fluorescent or better still, by light-emitting diodes (LEDs).
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is equivalent to 70% of the exhaust gases in the global fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, major emission emitters such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that would bring global CFC emissions down from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, from this balance sheet, one would have to subtract 5 Gt to stabilize the climate increase by 2 degrees Celsius between now and 2020, to prevent it from getting out of control.
In the white glowing bulbs, 95% of the energy escapes in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produces the light.
The compact fluorescent bulbs reduce energy consumption by 75%, while the new LED bulbs reduce this energy requirement by twice as much.
The compact fluorescent bulbs last on average between 6000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those that the manufacturer Philips launched this week – by the way, this company has participated in the UN study – have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a white glowing bulb, indicating the savings possibilities of the replacement plan, which is to be applied in 100 countries.
In addition to the fact that these completely novel light bulbs emit very little heat, they can also work with a control resistance.
They do not contain any mercury.
Several specialists have shown that compact fluorescent bulbs have reserves because they contain mercury and that they have to be disposed of as special waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless the producers provide a reception point.
The main source of mercury emissions on the planet, however, according to the report, is not the compact fluorescent bulb, but rather the coal-fired power plants that emit significantly more mercury to generate the electricity wasted by the white-glowing bulbs.
In the United States alone, these coal-fired power plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury annually.
The report details the profits that each country would make from this international programme.
Indonesia, for example, would save one billion dollars a year on electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, which is the equivalent of 3.5 coal-fired power plants, the construction of which would cost Indonesia 2.5 billion.
