The WikiLeaks case has two meanings.
On one hand, it has turned out to be an obvious scandal, a scandal that is merely a scandal in the sense of hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it heralds profound changes at the international level and gives a glimpse of the future dominated by regression.
But let's go one step further.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file created by an intelligence service (an x-any nation) consists exclusively of newspaper clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits throw away nothing more than what you've been reading for months anyway in every x-any journal (except those whose owner is Berlusconi), and Gaddafi's terrifyingly caricatured profile has been offering their cabaret artists their stuff for years.
The rule that the secret files must consist only of known news is essential for the dynamics of the intelligence services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a library dedicated to esoteric publications, you will realize that each work (about the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Chateau, the Templars or the Rosicrucians) repeats exactly what has already been written in previous works.
This is not because the author of occult texts does not want to publish any research (yet because he does not know where news about the non-existent could be found), but because those who dedicate themselves to occultism believe in nothing other than what they already know and confirm what they have already learned.
This is also Dan Brown’s success mechanism.
The same goes for secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited-minded) is also the head of the intelligence service (otherwise he could be anything, for example, editor at Libération), who only considers what he acknowledges to be true.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi that the American embassy in Rome had sent to the State Department was the same as those that Newsweek had published the week before.
Why, then, was such a nuisance made about the revelations of these dossiers?
On one side, they say what every educated person already knows, namely that the embassies – at least since the end of World War II and since then even the heads of government can call each other or take a plane to meet for dinner – have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of some small representation tasks, have turned into espionage centers.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is not out of hypocrisy that one does so to ignore it.
Nevertheless, the fact of repeating it publicly violates the task of hypocrisy and serves to put American diplomacy in a bad light.
Secondly, the idea that an x-any hacker can tap into the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world holds the significant blow against the prestige of the state department.
In addition, the scandal brings less the victims, rather than the "judges" in distress.
But let’s devote ourselves to the profound nature of what happened.
Formerly, in Orwell’s time, you could bundle all power like a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell’s prophecy could have since turned out to be perfectly correct, where you can control every movement thanks to the phone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the chosen highway and so on; the citizen would become the total victim of the eye of power.
But when one sees what is happening today that even the secret crypts of power can no longer escape the control of a hacker, the control system ceases to be one-sided and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker – chosen as the avenger of the citizen – can uncover the secrets of power.
But how can a power that is no longer able to keep its own secrets stand?
True, Georg Simmel has already said that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that any knowledge of Berlusconi’s or Merkel’s character is basically a secret free from secrecy, as it reveals the public sphere; but in the style of WikiLeaks were to reveal any robbery, that the secrets of Hillary Clinton’s secrets meant to be secrets.
WikiLeaks did neither Sarkozy nor Merkel wrong, but Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this offense inflicted on such a mighty power?
It is obvious that in the future, the states will no longer put any reserved information online - that would be like a sticking out on the street corner.
But it is equally obvious that with the current technologies it is in vain to hope to be able to keep confidential reports on the phone secret.
Nothing is easier than figuring out if and when a head of state travelled on a plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How could private relationships be maintained in the future and only for certain ears?
I know very well that my prediction at the moment sounds like science fiction and romance, but I feel compelled to imagine the government agents, secretly moving on uncontrollable routes, carrying their communications nowhere but in mere memory, and moreover the little written information they have received in Schuberg.
The information would be stored in a single copy in locked drawers: basically, Watergate’s espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is progressing nowadays like a cancer, namely backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communication, the Internet is reconstructing a telegraph using (telephone) wire.
The (analogous) video cassettes had allowed film researchers to explore a film band by band by spooling from the back to the front and uncovering all the secrets of the assembly, while the (numeric) CDs nowadays allow nothing but to jump from chapter to chapter, i.e. in macro-portions.
High-speed trains take you from Rome to Milan within three hours, while it takes three and a half hours by plane, including transfers.
It is therefore not uncommon for politics and communication technology to come back by car and horse.
One last observation.
In earlier times, the press tried to understand what secrets were forged between the messages.
At present, it is the messages that demand confidential information from the press.
