While the EU Commission had proposed harmonisation, certain member states, including France, have blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the guideline that they deem best.
For example, the EU Commission has chosen as the benchmark for 2009: international financing will be maintained, and under the "Fast-Start" funding, 150 million will be added over three years.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks, either in terms of the year or in terms of conditions at the level of public development assistance.
In return, France believed that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 was "new and additional".
In other words, there are no benchmarks for spending in the previous year or at the global level of public development assistance.
In concrete terms, the total amount of French support to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease) - France pretends to comply with its commitment to "new and additional" financing.
Another crucial element is the breakdown into donations and loans.
There is no rule on this yet, and everyone chooses their computational mode.
Some, such as France, find 1 € borrowed as equivalent to 1 € donated.
Obviously, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans for certain profitable investments (often related to emissions reduction projects based on the most effective technology) can be justified, it is misleading to present the euro that is taken as the equivalent of a donated euro... In addition, only the cost of the loan for the investor country should be counted as the rate of interest.
But France has nothing else in the sense than the following consideration: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by taking out 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and donating 8.5%) 36.1 million euros) - see also the EU document to convince itself of it.
France is the only country in the EU that uses large amounts of loans.
Germany is demanding 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among other things) are fulfilling their commitments 100% with donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union spends €1 to fulfil its obligations, France gives just 10 cents and understands a comparable use.
Beautiful Hokuspokus!
All in all, France operates in its fast-start financing with a double fraud: partly with a further development of the action over time and partly with the reality of the financial commitment.
France manages to make it believe that it has spent 420 million "new and additional" millions in accordance with its promises, saving 36.1 million euros.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (since it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitration) could have a double negative effect; once inside the EU (why do the other member states continue with the donation, if it is enough to lend?) and then in the negotiations, since the developing countries are not completely deceived...
The chapter of premature financing only a small question for a relatively short time compared to the totality of discussions about the climate.
But it could be the drop too much in the immense machinery of the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
However, it is essential to learn from this first year of early financing.
First and foremost, France could announce a change in its accounting method for the years 2011 and 2012, in the spirit of respect for its obligations and balancing justice with the other countries of the European Union.
Above all, however, France could bring forward the discussions on the issue of long-term financing (another issue that is crucial and currently under discussion): one does not escape the question of "predictability" or the way in which his loans are booked.
France could change its position to be as progressive on issues of dispute as it is on other things.
So the hope is based on the new environment minister Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprising announcement about France’s fast-start and its vision of “predictability” and the use of loans would naturally raise the international basis of trust necessary for further discussion.
Alarm - Pesticides taken by children
A 10-year-old child takes 81 different chemicals during the day, according to a study published this Wednesday by the Association Générations Futures (former movement to protect the rights and respect of future generations).
The association, which explains that its results "given the small number of samples analyzed do not reflect a statistically significant value, but represent an illustrative character of the problem treated", had bought between July and September the food usually consumed by a child of about ten years old at meals plus an intermediate meal in the supermarkets in Oise and Paris.
These typical meals – including the official recommendations of five fresh fruit and fruit parts, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day – have been studied as well as snacks from laboratories looking for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The dish balance is crushing: 81 chemical substances, including 42 classified as possibly or likely carcinogenic and five as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances with endocrine disruption factor, according to studies by several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
"Even if in the approximate totality of cases the legal limits for each chemical, individually taken substance are not exceeded, it is very clear from this survey that the reality in which the consumer is exposed to potentially carcinogenic substances or substances with endocrine disruption factor is alarming," notes the association.
Already at breakfast alone, butter and tea with milk already contain more than ten of the potentially carcinogenic residues and three safely proven to be carcinogenic, as well as more than twenty residues that can affect the hormonal system.
The apple imported from Brazil, intended as an intermediate meal for the study, has traces of six chemical substances, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to green beans from Kenya, including lunch, where the study found traces of an insecticide strictly prohibited in the EU.
In addition, the chopped steak, the tuna from the can, and even the baguette and chewing gum were sprayed with pesticides and other chemicals.
In the case of tap water, the analyses have revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon steak with 34 determined chemical residues was the "most rich", and even the plastic plate used to warm the meal in the microwave was not unloaded.
The ultimate risk of this “pollutant cocktail” for the consumer “is likely to be underestimated,” according to the study.
The Alliance Europe Ecologie-Les Verts (EE-LV) has proposed a moratorium on the use of pesticides in order to stop the "increase in diseases of civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) identified the presence of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
